showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=565.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> don't forget</span><hr size=1> You're trading your future reputation with people you screw for immediate plat. It is very ill advise to have your main character doing the trading.<br><br>I know a few of the EC merchants on my server. I will absolutely never deal with them in any way. I know that anything I have to do with them will end in me being given the short end of the stick and as a result, I will completely avoid them. I won't team them, and generally have no interest in talking to them.<br><br>On another note, using the right zones it is very easy to solo over 1200pp / hour with no risk or harm done to others. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/umemak.showPublicProfile?language=EN>memak</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Monk-in-Training</span><br>  Posts: 80<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(10/14/01 6:47:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=565.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: don't forget</span><hr size=1> The traders fill a roll in EQ just like every class in your group.  Some people like to play merchant and, believe it or not, are providing a valuable service that they deserve to be compensated for -- within reason!<br><br>Say I come across an item in some remote place that I don't need, none of my friends need, none or my twinks need.  I hate sitting in NFP for hours trying to get a good deal when I can be off eating exotic mobs and drinking their blood.  I'd much rather have a "trader" take it off my hands for a reasonable commission so I can get back to doing what I enjoy.<br><br>Say I want to improve my character but really don't feel like sitting at some stupid hour upon hour camp waiting on a rare green spawn to drop a rare item I want.  "Traders" know about these in damand items and I'm more than happy to pay them a reasonable commission to avoid boredom.<br><br>Commissions are sort of like a tax I'm willing to pay to avoid being a trader myself, because I enjoy doing other things. <p><P><font color=yellow><i>Memak ~ 58 Iksar Master<br>Memek Songwyver ~ 53 Halfelf Minstrel<br></font><font color=orange>Eternal Honor ~ Mithaniel Marr<br></font></i><br><b>This game is fun damnit!</b></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#778899><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/ulaotzuqigong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>LaotzuQigong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Monk</span><br>  Posts: 182<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(10/16/01 9:08:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=565.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Advanced trading.</span><hr size=1> Since we're on the topic, I guess I'll put in my 2 cp.<br><br>There are really only 4 ways to generate platinum in this game.<br><br>1)  Camp an item and sell it.<br>2)  Make an item and sell it.<br>3)  Make an item for someone else and charge a fee.<br>4)  Buy an item and then resell it.<br><br>Camping<br><br>This is probably the most common method of earning platinum in the game.  Basically, sit your butt down at a camp, hope an item drops, hope you win it, then go to your local auction zone and sell it.<br><br>This has one of the highest potential for earnings for time spent.  IE, an 8 hour camp can net you 10 or 20 k in items.  There are multiple downsides to this of course, you can only camp items of which you're of sufficient level and have access to the relevant zones.  Then there is the actual moving of the item.  Moving an item can take anywhere from 15 mins to 15 days depending on the item.<br><br>Small but high demand items tend to move fast, big high demand items tend to move slowly.<br><br>The more expensive the item, the more difficult it is to sell regardless of the level of demand.<br><br>I know that sounds strange, but think of things this way.  Everyone and their kid brother may want that 100 k CoF, but how many people actually HAVE 100 k plat sitting around in their bank accounts?  Not many... so you might get that nice 20 k item, but find that it can take days to weeks to sell.  Or even worse, find that Nobody can buy one because none of the people who want it can afford it.<br><br>Another major downside is item price deflation.  Hot items become very heavily camped making it difficult to supply a steady stream of these items, while over time flooding the market and pushing prices down over time.  Also, addition of new item content tends to heavily obsolete items, further pushing price value down.  Good examples of this are the FBSS, Yaks, Wurmslayers, etc.<br><br>Making Items for Sale<br><br>This falls under trade skills and questing.  IE, go out, collect components, make an item and resell.<br><br>Generally, cash earnings tend to be somewhat low, with the rare exception of Jewelcraft which has medium earning potential.  A good jeweller can probably net 10 to 20 k per week assuming they can get enough of the right components.<br><br>The major downsides to this is the time required to get components, the risk of material loss (failures), as well as steady depreciation of profit margins as more people gain skills in those trades.  Also, the costs of building trade skills can be exceptionally high.  Ranging from 2 k for basic master blacksmithing to in excess of 10 k for grandmaster Blacksmithing, 25 k for Jewelcraft, or 50 to 100 k for skills like Tinkering and Alchemy.<br><br>Making items for Fees<br><br>This falls under trade skills, however instead of manufacturing equipment from components, you simply hire out your skills as a service.<br><br>Cash earning tend to be quite low compared to camping or making items yourself as you're not getting a markup over component cost, however this is one of the most time efficient ways of making cash.  Since you don't collect components, nor do you need to camp items, you make cash anytime anyone needs something made.<br><br>Basically, you make yourself known as a master tradesman, and people contact you regarding the making of items.<br><br>There are multiple downsides, but none other than the time to acquire the skill are major.  These include the cost of the tradeskill (see above) and deflation of skill value as more people gain skills in your tradeskill.  Also, few people tend to pay for trade services unless your tradeskill is *VERY* rare.  People rarely pay for Jewelcraft (everyone has a 250 JC friend), though currently they will still sometimes pay for master Poison, Tinkering, Tailoring and Smithing services due to the tremendous time and costs of reaching 250 in those skills.<br><br>Finally, cash flow is of limited control. You cannot make cash whenever you wish as you need to both build a good reputation as a master tradesman as well as wait for customers to come to you.<br><br>Reselling Items (Middleman)<br><br>This is the most difficult of roads for making plat.<br><br>Essentially, the idea is to purchase items at below market value and then to resell them at current market value or slightly above current market value.<br><br>This requires tremendous time investment.  Those wishing to fulfill this role of middleman needs to master multiple skills including good interpersonal skills, a talent for selling, exceptional patience, all while maintaining constant awareness of server market conditions.<br><br>That being said, trading is probably the most lucrative and most consistent of the methods of earning plat in the game.  There are also multiple major advantages to trading.  Any person can become an in-game trader.  You can do it any time as long as you can get a port or mule to a trading zone.  The amount of money you have to start with doesn't have to be substantial and trades can scale up in size to accomodate your finances and skill level.  It is not limited by your level or class, does not require grouping, and is completely controlled by you.<br><br>That being said, there is considerable risk to trading items.  It is possible to lose plat, and Significant amounts.  I'm sure there's more than a few traders who have cursed themselves over that Mortificator's Staff or Argent Defender that they somehow picked up in a deal.  8P<br><br>Trading is somewhat more of an art than a science, and at it's highest levels can be very complex.<br><br>Since this thread is mostly about trading, I'll specifically address the concept of Trading and levels of complexity.<br><br>Types of Trades<br><br>Plat for gear - This is the simplest trade.  You find an item, buy it for plat at a hopefully good price, and then sell it for plat at hopefully a higher price.  Your profit margin can range tremendously depending upon the timing and your level of integrity.  Essentially, all this requires is a knowledge of the going price of an item to determine whether the buy/sell price is high or low.<br><br>Gear for Gear - This is the next most complex trade.  You have an item (acquired in some way), which you then trade for another item.  Hopefully, the trade works out in your favor as the item you trade for is of higher value than the item you traded away.  Price however is not entirely accurate, as utility often comes into play.  IE, if you NEED an item, you may trade at a loss in order to get that item.  Also, getting a straight item trade is often difficult, as the person who has the item you need does NOT necessarily *want* your item, nor do you want their's.<br><br>Gear + Plat for Gear - More complex than a straight trade in that you're trying to assess both the value of both items, as well as cover the price difference between the items with plat.  This trade complicates the situation as often plat can be a major sticking point.  So now you have the problem of finding someone to trade something you need for something they want or vice versa AND they or you need to have cash onhand.  Many people don't have huge bank accounts to add value to a trade, so executing this sort of trade consistently is more common than straight plat purchases.<br><br>Multi trades - This is the most complex form of trade and can range tremendously from hard to very difficult to assess.  The only thing common to this form of trade is that it usually involves multiple items on one or both sides And can include cash in the mix.<br><br>A typical example of a complex multitrade might be Fungi + Lamentation + 15 k in exchange for Bloodpoint + Mrylokar's Helm + Hiero Cloak + Blue Diamond Bracer.<br><br>There are multiple points of difficulty in making these sorts of trades.  First, you need comprehensive knowledge of item values across the board.  Second, if you're not going to use every item you acquire, you need to accomodate the time of selling as well as inventory space usage into your thought process.  Finally, the higher the total value of the trade, the harder it is to do successfully (IE, at a profit).<br><br>Laotzu's Basic Pointers....<br><br>Okay, so now you have some idea what's involved in trading, so here's some basic tips and rules that I like to go by...<br><br>1)  Integrity.  DON'T lie.  Ever.  Don't lie about the value of an item when you're selling.  You can ask a slightly higher than market price (like 10 to 20 percent), but don't tell someone a 1 k item is worth 10 k.  If someone mentions that they saw your 10 k item go for 8 k, no problem.  They can spend 2 days waiting for the next one to show up.<br><br>Yes, you can get a few more bucks by cheating someone, but if someone knows you deliberately charged them an exorbitant amount, it does nothing but hurt your customer base.  Not to mention, it will cost you in ports, rezzes, xp groups etc in the long run.<br><br>2)  Your word is your bond.  Once you make a deal, for good or for bad, go through with it.  Don't go back to market holding out for a higher price once you've agreed to a deal.  It might net you a few more plat that sale, but it will leave a bad taste in people's mouths, and word travels fast.<br><br>3)  Bargains.  Watch for items below market.  When you spot one, don't volunteer information.  If someone is selling an item for 1/2 of the going market price, don't offer them more.  Don't procrastinate.  Send a tell immediately, buy it, and then sell it at the correct market price.  If you feel uncomfortable with reselling it immediately, hold it for a day or two before you start auctioning.<br><br>4)  Desperate buyers.  Okay, sometimes a person comes along who KNOWS the current market price on an item, but really Wants to buy it and buy it right now.  In these situations, *ANY* price you agree on is fair.  As long as both of you know that the price is substantially above market price, then there's nothing wrong.  If a person is that desperate to get item_XXX today, this minute, this second, then they should expect to pay a premium.  They might say, &quot;But it only goes for X...&quot;.  On the other hand, you can always tell them, &quot;True, but that's the price I'm asking.&quot;<br><br>5)  Don't fall in love with a trade.  Always be willing to walk away.  Don't try to haggle if it's clear they're not going to haggle.  And never feel obligated to buy anything unless you've agreed to the deal.<br><br>6)  Don't be afraid to pay a premium if you truly NEED an item.  If you want to buy an item and it's something you need and will use for a long time, don't let price stand in your way unless you see it for sale 3x a day.  IE, that Cloak of Flames might theoretically only go for 80, but how often do you actually see one for sale?  If you actually NEED that CoF, IE you're not going to resell, then BUY IT even if it's a little expensive.  6 months of play time in that cool new piece of gear is worth Alot more than 6 months trying to save some plat here and there.<br><br>7)  Get off your duff and do some trading!<br><br>This should be enough to get anyone started.  Keep in mind, that trading is actually amazingly complex, and a person could probably write a huge multi-page document on successful trading in the EQ economy.<br><br>However, regardless of whatever guides are written, trading requires experience.  You just gotta get out there and do it.<br><br>If you're good, you can outfit your characters in whatever buyable gear you desire, AND have a bank account that makes people /boggle.<br><br>LaotzuQigong<br>60 Grandmaster<br>Legendary<br>The Tribunal <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/uskekofvazaelle.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Skek of Vazaelle</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Young Grasshoppah</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(10/18/01 2:55:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=565.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Advanced trading.</span><hr size=1> Ahh such inspiration and about 600pp sitting in my alts bank account <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br>Great oak trees grow from little acorns...I hope! <p>Skek.  Level ?? Monkly Leezard of Vazaelle.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#778899><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/us